<br>
I have a lot of characters which can buff.  At the same time, I have a lot of characters who would like buffs.<br>
<br>
Ultimately you have a couple things to look at.  If you want SoW on demand, you should play a Druid, Shaman, Beastlord or a Ranger.  If you would like clarity on demand, play an Enchanter or group with one.<br>
<br>
If I have the mana free, I will always give people buffs.  If the mana is not free, I offer to buff the person if they're willing to wait for my mana.  I usually ask people to come to me, if they would like a buff, just as I offer to go to someone, when requesting a buff from them.<br>
<br>
If a person is on roleplay or anon, they don't want to be bothered for a rez, clarity, gg, sow etc... so I won't ask the person.  But that's not to say others won't.<br>
<br>
If you don't want to be asked for buffs constantly, pick a class which cannot buff, gg, or rez.. maybe a warrior, rogue, monk, bard or something similar.  Not that my rogue (wood elf) is not sent 5 tells a night requesting sow or gg's. hehe.  Playing something like that precludes your ability to heal someone who is dying.. which is the downside to those classes.<br>
<br>
I don't like the tells from people who ask you to leave your group or hate raid, and travel to them to give them a sow or rez.  The tell is not a problem, its when the person gets rude and indignant when you turn them down.  Ultimately if I'm free, I'll travel to help people.. If I'm grouped or doing something for myself, I'll ask people to come to me.  Each person has to figure out what they're comfortable with.<br>
<br>
A friend offers to do rez's, but charges 100pp per zone they have to travel to get to the corpse.  That is one way to discourage people from asking for stuff from you, but it can also precludes your receiving a favor from them..  Personally I always charge either a /hug or a donation of the other persons choice, but that's me.<br>
<br>
With regards to buffs, it helps to look back to my first guild.. "Order of the Red Claw".  We were not huge or terribly powerful, but we were very friendly and helpful.  When things were going poorly or someone was trained, I remember a couple clerics who would always go out of their way to help.  Murrachan Moorsfang was one of them.. *smiles*.  <br>
<br>
Remembering how a buff here or there, or having someone always there to help you makes you feel so good, is important for us.  We can return that to others, as a class capable of giving those buffs.  I love to give random buffs to lots of people, hopefully helping to make their day too. <p><BR>
